results.notes:
Mulchbed on north side of Philip Fulmer Way directly south of Tom Black Track at LaPorte Stadium. Growing partially buried in mulch under shrubs near Acer sp. Basidiocarps abundant, epigeous, clustered and attached to white rhizomorphs by several points of attachment. Basidiocarps 5.6 to 18.2 mm wide and 4.8 to 12.0 mm tall, some anostomosing. Peridium externally white (2.5Y 9.5/1 in Munsell) to very pale yellow (2.5Y 9.5/2), dry and smooth, partially encrusted with debris, composed of a very thin exoperidium from which the rhizomorphs and a thicker, solid endoperidium. Endoperidium white (2.5Y 9.5/1) externally and translucent in cross-section; 0.2 to 0.5 mm thick, clearly demarcated from gleba and easily separated from it. Gleba yellow (10YR 8/8, 10YR 7/8) to brownish yellow (10YR 6/8) [closest colors in Munsell, more vibrant than these]; firm and compact; not gelatinized; not reacting with Melzer’s reagent; with small chambers separated by thin white veins; lacking clearly differentiated columellas. Odor strong and complex: fruity (like mango and sour apples) with a foul/skunky/chemical component, somewhat like marijuana/hops, ammonia, urine and acetone. Taste farinose and slightly fruity. All gleba structures inamyloid. Clamps present in the gleba. Basidia 3-sterigmate to 4-sterigmate. Sterigmata apices remaining breaking and remaining attached to some spores. Spores spiny and thick-walled. Spore measurements: (6.8) 7.3 – 8.6 (9) × (5.8) 6 – 7.9 (8.7) µm; Q = (1) 1.1 – 1.3 (1.4); N = 30; Me = 7.9 × 6.9 µm; Qe = 1.1

results.notes:
Collected with Jacob Kalichman. Growing abundantly on the mossy bark of a live standing Aesculus sp. Gills very pale orange (color not in Munsell); not marginate; adnexed; some forked; with 2 to 4 tiers of lamellulae. 24 full-length lamellae reaching the stem. Stems initially white and becoming very pale yellow (2.5Y 9.5/2 to 2.5Y 9/2) after picking; dry; finely pruinose; equal; solid; not releasing liquid when cut; lacking basal discs; with sparse white basal mycelium; 12.4 to 33.6 mm long and 0.7 to 0.9 mm wide. Odor and taste not distinctive. Spore print white. All lamellar structures inamyloid. Lamellar trama regular. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia absent or scarce. Cheilocystidia abundant, hyaline, smooth and thin-walled; ovoid to fusiform. Basidioles clavate and basally clamped. Spores pip-shaped or rarely almost heart-shaped, inamyloid, hyaline, smooth and thin-walled. results.notes:
I found this on the ground where there is a lot of organic debris (dead leaves, branches, mulch) accumulated for many years, right next to a tree (not sure what kind, but it’s not conifer. I may update with tree name later).

The mushroom started out as some kind of ball, because once it “breaks”, there’s a volva underneath. The size of the ball, cap and volva is huge though, 3-4 inches across. The volva itself is a big blob of “mushroom material”, which is all white throughout.

The stipe is 3/4 to 1 inch thick, although one (old) specimen I see has a thinner (1/2 inch) and longer (5 inch) stipe. Maybe it gets thinner in old age? The skin of stipe is not smooth, it has these fiber strands as if it’s shedding (similar to how a eucalyptus shed its bark).

The fresh mushroom is white all-around, with dirt attaching to the top of cap. If I cut the stipe, it has somewhat off-white color, turning to rust in old age.

However if I cut the cap, the color is dark maroon. In fact, the white outer layer on the cap is very thin, just like a skin. Underneath all that is a dark rusty/maroony color, even on young/fresh mushrooms. It looks very thick and dense.

The oddest thing on this mushroom is the lack of gill or pores. I cannot find anything like that on the underneath of the cap. It looks like a membrane or continuous skin. It’s like that even for old and mature mushrooms. I know it doesn’t make sense (how/where does it release spores?) but that’s what it looks like. I’ll enclose a close-up of the underneath of 2 of them (one fresh and one mature). The cap is fully developed for both of them, yet I can find no sign of gill or open-mouth pores.

The smell is not like your typical mushroom. It’s somewhat musty, and I would say exotic (I know this is vague), but not unpleasant.

What can it be? I’ve searched my field guide but can’t find anything.

results.notes:
white crust with brownish apothecia. thallus UV+orange (I somehow lost the piece before doing any spot tests!).

I took an apothecial section from 2 apothecia that were kind of smushed together, seen in the close up pic of the thallus/apothecia. Under the microscope, I noticed some subtle differences between the 2 apothecia that made me wonder if it is possibly 2 different species? Perhaps the apothecia were just of different age or something, which caused these apparent differences? What I saw, or interpreted, was the following (I will call the apothecia #1 and #2): 1.) one of the apothecia had paraphyses with visible (and prominent) septa [#1], while the other did not. 2.) the asci in one apothecia appeared truncated at the tip [#1], while the other’s asci were rounded. 3.) While the spores were roughly the same size/shape, there were cosmetic differences between them (obviously, this could just be due to age). 4.) Epihymenium of #1 had more of a brown color and appeared thicker than #2, which had more of a green color.

And, it is entirely possible I completely misinterpreted what I saw…

Growing under Doug fir in burned area

Odor was noticeable and unusual and a bit hard to describe (Stuntz describes it as follows: sharp, penetrating (though not strong), spermatic for an instant when flesh first exposed, immediately becoming complex, a mixture of radish-like and resinous with component of vinegar.)

No pleurocystidia, cheilocystidia thick-walled

100% match to type of Inocybe picrosma

Stuntz describes the species as follows
Inocybe picrosma is characterized especially by its unique odor, described as a mixture of radish-like and resinous with a vinegar component. CAP 1.5-4cm, pale creamy yellow to pale buff, sometimes flushed darker especially on disc, appressed silky-fibrillose, smooth and shiny at first, usually becoming scaly. GILLS adnexed to narrowly adnate, close, moderately broad, pallid in color when young. STEM 2.5-8.5cm x 0.3-0.7cm, equal with a flat bulb which may be abrupt, pale yellow becoming flushed dull vinaceous brown or fuscous brown, the margin of the bulb usually with a flush of salmon, satiny-shining, longitudinally hygrophanous-lined, white-pruinose at first, remaining so at top. ODOR sharp, penetrating (though not strong), spermatic for an instant when flesh first exposed, immediately becoming complex, a mixture of radish-like and resinous with component of vinegar. TASTE a little astringent and peppery at first, soon becoming mild and almost sweet, but leaving an unpleasant aftertaste. MICROSTRUCTURES spores 7-10(11) x 5-6 um, almond-shaped; pleurocystidia 36-60(63) x 16.5-21 um, fusiform-clavate, with obtuse apex and slender pedicel, very thick-walled above, cheilocystidia of two kinds, some similar to pleurocystidia in size and shape, others clavate, thin-walled, 22-56 × 8-11.5 um. REMARKS I. kauffmanii has a stem that does not become vinaceous brown and a different odor. I. suaveolens has a sweet odor and different microscopic characteristic
